This is the first in a short series of tutorials on neural simulation-based
inference (SBI) in R. It covers the basics: what problem SBI solves, the three
ingredients every analysis needs, and what it means for a fit to be
*amortized*. Later tutorials go deeper on density estimators, calibration, and
applied case studies -- this one stays small on purpose.

## The problem

Ordinary Bayesian inference needs a likelihood, `p(x | theta)`: a formula for
how likely the data are, given the parameters. For a simulator -- code that
generates synthetic data by drawing random numbers internally -- that formula
often does not exist. The simulator can produce data all day long; it just
cannot tell you the probability of any particular output. SBI sidesteps the
likelihood entirely: it learns the posterior directly from (parameter,
simulated-data) pairs.

A concrete example. The **g-and-k distribution** is a flexible model for
skewed, heavy-tailed data -- rainfall totals, incomes, financial returns --
defined not by a density but by its quantile function: transform a standard
normal draw `z` through

```
Q(z) = A + B * (1 + 0.8 * tanh(g * z / 2)) * (1 + z^2)^k * z
```

and the result is a draw from the distribution. `A` and `B` are location and
scale; `g` and `k` control skew and tail weight. Simulating is a one-liner.
But writing down the density means inverting `Q()`, which has no closed form
-- so the likelihood genuinely is not available, even though generating data
is trivial. This is exactly the setting SBI targets, and it is why the
distribution is a standard test case in the likelihood-free literature
(Rayner & MacGillivray, 2002; Prangle, 2020).

We will treat `g` and `k` as known (2 and 0.5) and infer the location `A` and
scale `B` from a small sample of observations.

## The three ingredients

Every SBI problem needs a **prior**, a **simulator**, and an **observation**.

```{r}
library(neuralsbi)   # note: masks base::sample -- see below

# (1) prior over the two parameters we want to infer
prior <- prior_uniform(low = c(0, 0.3), high = c(10, 2))

# (2) simulator: an (n x 2) matrix of parameters -> an (n x 10) matrix of data.
# Each row draws 10 i.i.d. observations from the g-and-k distribution at that
# row's (A, B), with g = 2 and k = 0.5 fixed.
rgk <- function(n, A, B, g = 2, k = 0.5, c = 0.8) {
  z <- rnorm(n)
  A + B * (1 + c * tanh(g * z / 2)) * (1 + z^2)^k * z
}
simulator <- function(theta) {
  t(apply(theta, 1, function(th) rgk(10, th[1], th[2])))
}

# (3) the observation: 10 measurements from a population with A = 3, B = 1
theta_true <- c(A = 3, B = 1)
x_obs <- simulator(rbind(theta_true))
```

`neuralsbi` masks `base::sample()` with an S3 generic so that `sample(post,
n)` can dispatch on a fitted posterior; `sample(1:10, 3)` still works as
usual, and `sample_posterior()` is a non-generic alias if the masking gets in
the way in a script.

One more thing worth flagging up front, especially if you come from
regression or Stan: SBI writes the *observed data* as `x`, the role your
outcome variable `y` usually plays. Covariates, if you have any, are absorbed
into the simulator. It takes a page or two to stop mentally substituting `y`.

## Training an amortized posterior estimator

`npe()` (Neural Posterior Estimation) draws parameters from the prior, runs
the simulator, and trains a **density estimator** -- here a masked
autoregressive flow (Papamakarios et al., 2017), the package default -- to
approximate `p(theta | x)` directly from those pairs. No likelihood function
appears anywhere in this call.

```{r}
# 5000 simulations for a 2-parameter posterior. If the fit below looks too
# wide or the calibration check is off, add simulations before reaching for a
# bigger network.
fit <- npe(prior, simulator, n_simulations = 5000, seed = 1)
fit
```

This fit is **amortized**: trained once, over the whole prior, it can be
conditioned on *any* observation afterwards -- no re-simulating, no
retraining. That is the central practical payoff of NPE over MCMC-based
approaches, which restart from scratch for every new data set.

## Conditioning on the observation

```{r fig.alt = "Pairs plot of the posterior over A and B, with the true values marked."}
post   <- posterior(fit, x_obs = x_obs)
draws  <- sample(post, 5000)
colnames(draws) <- c("A", "B")

summary(draws)
pairplot(draws, truth = theta_true)
```

The posterior concentrates around `A = 3, B = 1` -- the values that generated
`x_obs` -- with honest uncertainty from only 10 observations per data set.

## What amortization buys you

Condition the *same* fit on a second, unrelated observation. There is no
simulation and no training here -- just a forward pass through the network
already trained above.

```{r fig.alt = "Pairs plot of the posterior for a second observation, from the same fitted estimator."}
theta_true2 <- c(A = 6, B = 0.6)
x_obs2      <- simulator(rbind(theta_true2))

draws2 <- sample(posterior(fit, x_obs = x_obs2), 5000)
pairplot(draws2, truth = theta_true2, labels = c("A", "B"))
```

Reusing `fit` here is the point: an MCMC sampler would need to re-run its
chains for `x_obs2`; the amortized posterior just looks up a new conditional
density.

## Checking the fit

A trained estimator always returns *something* -- samples, a mean, credible
intervals -- whether or not the fit is any good. Checking calibration is part
of the workflow, not an optional extra. **Simulation-based calibration
(SBC)** does this without needing a known answer: draw `theta` from the
prior, simulate `x`, and see where the true `theta` ranks among posterior
draws given that `x`. Calibrated posteriors put the truth anywhere in that
ranking with equal probability, so the ranks come out uniform.

```{r fig.alt = "SBC rank histogram and expected-coverage plot for the fit."}
res <- sbc(fit, simulator, n_sbc = 200, n_posterior_samples = 300, seed = 2)
res                # per-parameter uniformity p-values (large = calibrated)

plot_sbc(res, param = 1)   # rank histogram for A: flat = calibrated
plot_coverage(res)         # empirical vs. nominal credible-interval coverage
```

`A`'s ranks are close to flat and its coverage curve tracks the diagonal
throughout. `B` is not quite there: its coverage dips modestly below the
diagonal over the middle of the range -- a nominal 65% interval covers closer
to 55% -- the signature of mild overconfidence. That is a realistic outcome
for a first pass, not a failure: with only 10 observations per data set,
scale is harder to pin down than location, and the fix is more simulations
before reaching for a bigger network. `vignette("diagnostics")` covers the
full set of checks, including what to do when a fit does not pass one.

## Where to go next

This tutorial covered the minimum: prior, simulator, observation, an
amortized fit, and one calibration check. It deliberately skipped almost
everything else --

- `vignette("neuralsbi")` walks the same workflow again with a
  linear-Gaussian model, where you can check the estimated posterior against
  an exact analytic answer.
- `vignette("density-estimators")` compares the mixture-density-network,
  flow, and closed-form estimators, and when each is worth using.
- `vignette("diagnostics")` covers the complete diagnostic toolkit: SBC,
  expected coverage, TARP, and posterior predictive checks.
- `vignette("sir-epidemic")` is a full applied case study, including
  sequential inference when simulations are expensive and only one
  observation matters.

For the ideas behind the method: Cranmer, Brehmer & Louppe (2020), ["The
frontier of simulation-based
inference"](https://www.pnas.org/doi/10.1073/pnas.1912789117), is a short,
readable review. Papamakarios & Murray (2016), ["Fast
&epsilon;-free inference of simulation models with Bayesian
conditional density
estimation"](https://arxiv.org/abs/1605.06376), introduced the approach NPE
descends from. Talts et al. (2018), ["Validating Bayesian inference
algorithms with simulation-based
calibration"](https://arxiv.org/abs/1804.06788), is the reference for the SBC
check used above. Lueckmann et al. (2021), ["Benchmarking simulation-based
inference"](https://arxiv.org/abs/2101.04653), compares NPE against the
other neural SBI algorithms this package does not implement (NLE, NRE) --
useful context for where `neuralsbi` sits in the broader landscape. Rayner &
MacGillivray (2002) and Prangle (2020) -- the latter's
[`gk`](https://journal.r-project.org/articles/RJ-2020-010/) package -- cover
the g-and-k distribution itself.
